Introduction¶

Why use U.S. Census data in climate research?¶

U.S. Census data is one of the predominate sources for information on population size, particularly when disaggregated by age, sex, race/ethnicity or other demographic and economic variables. Moreover, it is one of the only datasets providing. nationally-representative demographic and economic information on households and housing units. Data is collected every 10 years via the Decennial Census of Population and Housing, but the American Community Surve (ACS) is an annual survey of households designed to be nationally representative that collects more in-depth information about households and their members than the decennial Census.

It would be impossible to summarize the full array of questions asked in the ACS, but one particularly relevant question is related to household member migration:

Question 15a. Did this person live in this house or apartment 1 year ago? Possible answers:

  • Person is under 1 year old $\rightarrow$ SKIP to question 16
  • Yes, this house $\rightarrow$ SKIP to question 16
  • No outside the United States and Puerto Rico - Print name of foreign country or U.S. Virgin Islands, Guam, etc. below then SKIP to question 16
  • No, different house in the United States or Puerto Rico.

Question 15b. Where did this person live 1 year ago? Answer fields are: Address, Name of city, town, or post office, Name of U.S. county or municipio in Puerto Rico, Name of U.S. state or Puerto Rico, and ZIP Code.

Other Census datasets include the Population Estimates Program (annual post-censal population and housing units estimates for each state, county, and jurisdiction), the Current Population Survey (ongoing surveys on household membership and labor force participation), and many datasets on economic indicators.

Census geographies and uncertainty¶

Census data is available at a wide array of spatial resolution, and availability varies by data source. Figure 1 shows the hierarchy of Census geographies. Those geographies that can be built from the basic Census geographic unit, the Census block, like along the vertical "geographic spine". Certain data products are also produced for some of the "off-spine" geographies in Figure 1.

Decennial Census data is available at all geographies on the spine, but the introduction of differential privacy in the 2020 Decennial Census results in published counts that have more uncertainty at the smallest geographies of the spine. 2020 counts for the nation, states and large counties are reported with no uncertainty.

Aggregated, area-level ACS data is available annually at the national, state, and large county or city levels (65,000 or more). Uncertainty in these estimates arise from the sampling variability inherent in the household sampling scheme. Though data is collected annually, data is only shared publicly at the Census tract and block group level using 5-years of data. Sub-samples of ACS microdata, or person-level data, can be accessed for larger levels of geographies as well.

Why access Census data with R or Python?¶

Many Census data tables are available for download as Excel files or .csv's via the Census website and through this interactive Census website. However, accessing this data is not always reproducible. Moreover, you often need to download data for bigger geographic areas than may be of interest to you. Many packages and services exist to incorporate the downloading and accessing of specific variables for specific geographies into a reproducible workflow within R or Python. In addition, these packages often do much of the necessary "heavy-lifting" required to get the data into an easy-to-use format for other data science, GIS, or statistical programming tasks.

This tutorial will provide you with the necessary tools to access the Census data you need in a reproducible and simple way.

Tutorial Outline¶

The rest of this tutorial is organized as follows. Section 2 introduces the Census API and Python-based packages for accessing Census data. Section 3 provides an in-depth introduction to using the census library to query the Census API. Finally, Section 6 provides an important overview of how to aggregate Census tract data up to larger geographies that may be of importance to research or policy-makers but are not available in Census data.

Accessing Census Bureau Data with Python Packages¶

The Census API and census¶

The Census Application Programming Interface (API) is a tool built by the Census Bureau to allow for the downloading of public use Census data in an easy and systematic way. The Census API can be queried by anyone with the internet and a Census API Key (a unique-to-you alphanumeric code issued by the Census Bureau). It is constructed so you can specify the dataset and year you want, the specific variables you want within that dataset, and the geography for which you want the information within a formulaic URL in a relatively intuitive way. (See examples.) Though you can type these URLs into your internet browser, using functions within R or Python to visit certain URLs that query the API allow for a reproducible workflow. This online Census Bureau course is useful for those interested in learning more about the Census API

The census package (PyPI, GitHub, Author website) is a Python library written by Jonathan Carbah and maintained by Forest Gregg and Derek Eder that provides a suite of functions that facilitate the construction and implementation of Census API URL queries for several US Census API endpoints, focusing mainly on data from the ACS and the Decennial Census (SF1 and PL datasets).

IPUMS, NHGIS, and ipumspy¶

IPUMS provides democratized census and survey data from around the world integrated across time and space. It is the world’s largest accessible database of census microdata, which includes almost a billion records from U.S. censuses from 1790 to the present and over a billion records from the international censuses of over 100 countries.

Beyond census and survey microdata, IPUMS integrates and disseminates area-level census data and electronic boundaries describing census geography for the U.S. and internationally through its National Historical Geographic Information System (NHGIS). NHGIS provides easy access to summary tables and time series of population, housing, agriculture, and economic data, along with GIS-compatible mapping files for all census geographies from 1790 through the present.

The ipumspy library (User Guide, GitHub) provides a Python interface for handling IPUMS data allowing for users to read files downloaded from the IPUMS extract system, request data, download files, and get metadata from certain IPUMS collectionsm, and process data using the contextual information that is included with many IPUMS files.

pandas, us, and geopandas¶

The pandas library (PyPI, GitHub) is a powerful and flexible Python library for data analysis and manipulation. It provides data structures like Series and DataFrames that allow you to work efficiently with structured data, similar to how tidycensus organizes Census data in R. pandas is widely used for handling tabular data, enabling operations like filtering, grouping, joining, and aggregating data with ease. Its ability to integrate with other libraries makes it an essential tool for data analysis in Python.

The us library (PyPI, GitHub) is a lightweight Python package that simplifies working with metadata related to U.S. states and territories. It offers easy access to state names, abbreviations, and FIPS codes, which are crucial when working with U.S. Census data. The library allows for seamless integration with other tools and datasets, making it a valuable resource for geographic data analysis.

The geopandas library (PyPI, GitHub) extends pandas to support geospatial data operations. It allows you to work with geographic data in Python by reading, manipulating, and visualizing spatial datasets such as shapefiles, GeoJSON, and more. geopandas provides functionality similar to tigris in R by enabling spatial joins, overlays, and other geometric operations, as well as integrating with matplotlib for geographic plotting. It is the go-to library for spatial data analysis and mapping in Python.

The remainder of this tutorial will focus on using the census library to access Census data, and pandas, us, and geopandas to work with the data.

Getting and managing your Census API key¶

To use the census library you need to request your Census API key. This process is quick! Your own personal API key will be delivered to the email address provided.

One challenge with using these packages in a reproducible and group-based workflow is the management of API keys. Each member of the team who will be using any code that queries the Census APIs needs their own API key. API keys are not meant to be shared.

One nice work around is to have everyone in a group create their own Python script such as the file CensusAPIKey.py in Figure 2. This purpose will assign an individual's Census API code to a character object with a common name. In this example, everyone's API character string is assigned to an object called myKey.

When initializing your group's GitHub repository, add the name of this file to your .gitignore file as in Figure 3. NB: It's best to do this before adding the CensusAPIKey.py to your repository.

Once your .gitignore is modified and pushed, every team member can have their own CensusAPIKey.py file on their own machine that is never pushed to GitHub. Your team's code can be written in such a way that if CensusAPIKey.py is sourced in a script, every time an API key is needed a reference to the object myKey will be sufficient regardless of which team member is executing code. See example using census below.

In [ ]:
# import libraries
from census import Census
from us import states

### Load Census API Key ####
# Assuming your CensusAPIKey.py file is in the same directory as your script
from CensusAPIKey import myKey

### Set session API key in Census library ####
c = Census(myKey)

Using pandas, census, us, and geopandas¶

The pandas, census, us, and geopandas libraries in Python together provide powerful functionality for accessing and analyzing U.S. Census data. There are extensive resources available to help users get started with these libraries. The official documentation for each library and various tutorials provide ample guidance for both beginners and advanced users.

Selecting variables and tables¶

To access Census data via the census library in Python, you need to know the following information:

•	The dataset (e.g., ACS, Decennial Census),
•	The specific variable name,
•	The year of data you want,
•	The geographic level for the data (e.g., state, county),
•	The temporal scale for ACS data (1-year or 5-year),
•	Your Census API key.

In the subsections below, we briefly discuss the selection process and how it relates to querying Census data with the census library in Python. Following that, we provide full start-to-finish examples of querying both the Decennial Census and ACS data.

Datasets¶

The dataset you choose in the census Python library will determine the method used to query the Census API.

To access Decennial Census data, use the .sf1 method, which corresponds to Summary File 1 (SF1) data collected every ten years. For American Community Survey (ACS) data, you can use the .acs5 method for 5-year estimates, acs3 for 3-year estimates, or the .acs1 method for 1-year estimates. Additionally, the library provides access to specialized ACS Data Profiles and Subject Tables through the .acs5dp, .acs1dp, and .acs5st methods.

Variable & table names¶

In the Census API and the census library, a variable is uniquely defined by its name, which is typically an alphanumeric code. To retrieve the actual data values, use the get() method combined with the dataset attribute (e.g., .acs1, .acs5, .decennial, .sf1) and the variable names.

According to the PyPI documentation, the get() method is the core data access method on both the ACS and SF1 data sets. The first parameter is either a single string column or a tuple of columns. The second parameter is a geoemtry dict with a for key and on option in key. The for argument accepts a “*” wildcard character or Census.ALL. The wildcard is not valid for the inparameter.

By default, the year for a dataset is the most recent year available. To access earlier data, pass a year parameter to the API call:

A variable's name is passed as a character string to the NAME argument of the .get() functions. This is the unique identifier for a variable, usually in the format of a table ID followed by a numeric suffix. For example, "B01001_001E".

•    The prefix (e.g., "B01001") identifies the table.
•    The numeric part (e.g., "001") identifies the specific variable within that table.
•    The suffix "E" typically stands for "Estimate" (as opposed to "M" for "Margin of Error").

If you would like to select more than one variable in the same API query, you can directly pass the name of the variables to the NAME argument. For example, (NAME,'B01001_001E', 'B01001_002E').

The .tables() method retrieves metadata about the tables available in a specific Census dataset for a given year. It provides information about the structure and content of the data tables without actually fetching the data itself. Each table dictionary typically includes:

•   'name': The table identifier (e.g., 'B01001'),
•   'description': A brief description of what the table contains,
•   'variables': A URL to get more detailed information about the variables in this table,
•   'universe ': (Note the space) The population or subset that the table describes
In [ ]:
tables = c.acs1.tables(year=2021)

# Find the B01001 table
b01001_info = next((table for table in tables if table['name'] == 'B01001'), None)

if b01001_info:
    print("\nTable Information:")
    print(f"Name: {b01001_info['name']}")
    print(f"Description: {b01001_info['description']}")
    print(f"Universe: {b01001_info['universe ']}") # an extra space at the end of the key 'universe'
    print(f"Variables URL: {b01001_info['variables']}")
else:
    print("Table B01001 not found")

Table Information:
Name: B01001
Description: SEX BY AGE
Universe: Total population
Variables URL: http://api.census.gov/data/2021/acs/acs1/groups/B01001.json

The Variables URL provides a detailed description of each variable in the table, including its name, label, concept, and other attributes.

Data Year¶

In the Python census library, both the ACS and Decennial Census methods have a year argument. The usage of this argument varies slightly depending on the dataset:

  • For Decennial Census data (using .pl or .sf1), and ACS 1-year data (using .acs1), the year argument specifies the census year you want data for.
  • For ACS 3-year and 5-year data (using .acs3, or .acs5), the year argument can be used to specify the end year of the 3-year or5-year period for which you want data. For example, year=2021 for ACS 5-year will fetch data for the period 2017-2021.

Geographic Scale¶

Both the Decennial Census and ACS methods require you to specify the geographic level at which you want to retrieve data. This is done through the second argument of the get() method, which is a dictionary specifying the geographic parameters. The geographic scale is specified using the 'for' key in this dictionary. Some common geographic levels include:

  • State level: {'for': 'state:*'}
  • County level: {'for': 'county:*'}
  • Census tract level: {'for': 'tract:*'}
  • Place level: {'for': 'place:*'}

You can also specify nested geographies using the 'in' key. For example, to get data for all counties within a specific state:

In [ ]:
{'for': 'county:*', 'in': 'state:06'}  # All counties in California (FIPS code 06)
Out[ ]:
{'for': 'county:*', 'in': 'state:06'}

The exact geographies available may vary depending on the specific dataset (Decennial Census or ACS) and the year of data you're requesting. Always refer to the Census Bureau's documentation for the most up-to-date information on available geographies for each dataset.

Temporal Scale¶

Once you've determined your dataset of interest and your geographic scale, you're ready to specify your temporal scale. In the census library, this is typically handled through the choice of method and the year argument.

  • Decennial Census For the decennial Census, you'll be requesting data at a single year scale regardless of your geography. In the Python census library, you use different methods depending on the Census year: For 2020: Use the c.pl method (PL 94-171 Redistricting Data), For 2010 and earlier: Use the c.sf1 method (Summary File 1)
In [ ]:
# Example for 2020 Decennial Census
data = c.pl.get(('NAME', 'P1_001N'), {'for': 'state:*'}, year=2020)

# Example for 2010 Decennial Census
data = c.sf1.get(('NAME', 'P001001'), {'for': 'state:*'}, year=2010)

  • American Community Survey (ACS) For the ACS, you'll be requesting data at either the 1-year or 5-year scale, depending on your choice of geography. The censuslibrary provides different methods for these:

    For 1-year ACS: Use the c.acs1 method

    For 5-year ACS: Use the c.acs5 method

For national, state, and large counties or cities (Census places), you can usually use the 1-year ACS:

In [ ]:
data = c.acs1.get(('NAME', 'B01001_001E'), {'for': 'state:*'}, year=2021)

For small counties or places, tracts, or block groups, you'll almost certainly need to use the 5-year ACS:

In [ ]:
data = c.acs5.get(('NAME', 'B01001_001E'), {'for': 'tract:*', 'in': 'state:06'}, year=2021)

Querying the Census API¶

Using c.pl.get() for Decennial Census¶

Below we provide code for pulling counts of total housing units for each county in the state of Washington from the 2020 decennial Census using the following information:

  • Dataset: Decennial Census: .pl
  • Dataset-specific variables: Total housing units: H1_001N
  • The annual timeframe: 2020
  • Geographic Level: all counties in the state of 'WA'
  • Temporal Scale: Single year of 2020
  • Your Census API key
In [ ]:
# Load all libraries if not already loaded
# from census import Census
# import pandas as pd

from us import states
# Assuming you've already set up your Census object with your API key
c = Census(myKey)

# Get 2020 Decennial Census data
hu_wa_2020 = c.pl.get(
    ("NAME", "H1_001N"),
    {'for': 'county:*', 'in': f'state:{states.WA.fips}'},
    year=2020
)

# Convert to DataFrame for easier viewing
hu_wa_2020_df = pd.DataFrame(hu_wa_2020)
print(hu_wa_2020_df.head())

1   Asotin County, Washington  10034.0    53    003
2   Benton County, Washington  80076.0    53    005
3   Chelan County, Washington  37267.0    53    007
4  Clallam County, Washington  37930.0    53    009

A note on GEOIDs of the output¶

The GEOID column of output includes the standard Census numeric code for a particular geography. States and counties are determined by their Federal Information Processing Series(FIPS) codes. In the example above, we use the us library to get the FIPS code for Washington state. The output of the c.pl.get() function includes a county ID for each county in Washington state. The structure of the GEOID is as follows:

The state code is 2 digits long, Washington's FIPS code is 53.

The county code within each state is 3 digits long. Adams County's unique code within Washington is 001, so we see 001 in the county column for Adams County.

The tract code that uniquely identifies a Census tract within a county is 6 digits long. The resulting GEOID for a tract in Adams County, Washington is then 53001TTTTTT, where TTTTTT represents a 6-digit tract code.

The block group code that uniquely identifies each Census block group within a certain Census tract, TTTTTT, within Adams County, Washington is 1 digit long. The resulting GEOID for a block group within tract TTTTTT in Adams County, Washington is 53001TTTTTTG, where G represents a 1 digit tract code.

The block code that uniquely identifies each Census block within a block group, G, within a certain Census tract, TTTTTT, within Adams County, Washington is 3 digits long. The resulting GEOID for a block group within tract TTTTTT and block group G in Adams County, Washington is 53001TTTTTTGBBB, where BBB represents a 3 digit tract code.

Using c.acs1.get()for ACS Data¶

Below we provide code for pulling counts of individuals by sex for King County, Washington from the 2021 ACS using the following information:

  • Dataset: American Community Survey: .acs1,
  • Dataset-specific variables: total male (002) and female (026) population in the "SEX BY AGE" table: B01001_002E and B01001_026E,
  • The annual timeframe: 2021
  • Geographic Level: all tracts in the state of 'WA'
  • Temporal Scale: Single year of 2021
  • Your Census API key

Note: Different from tidycensus in R, In the Python census library, we need to explicitly request both the estimate ('E' suffix) and margin of error ('M' suffix) for each variable.

In [ ]:
# Get 2021 ACS 1-year data for King County, WA
pop_sex_king_2021 = c.acs1.get(
    ("NAME", "B01001_002E", "B01001_002M", "B01001_026E", "B01001_026M"),
    {'for': 'county:033', 'in': f'state:{states.WA.fips}'},
    year=2021
)

# Convert to DataFrame
pop_sex_king_2021_df = pd.DataFrame(pop_sex_king_2021)

# Rename columns for clarity
pop_sex_king_2021_df.columns = ['NAME', 'Male_Estimate', 'Male_MOE', 'Female_Estimate', 'Female_MOE', 'state', 'county']

# Reshape to long format
pop_sex_king_2021_long = pd.melt(
    pop_sex_king_2021_df, 
    id_vars=['NAME', 'state', 'county'],
    value_vars=['Male_Estimate', 'Female_Estimate', 'Male_MOE', 'Female_MOE'],
    var_name='temp_var',
    value_name='value'
)

# Separate the temporary variable into 'variable' and 'measure'
pop_sex_king_2021_long[['Sex', 'measure']] = pop_sex_king_2021_long['temp_var'].str.split('_', expand=True)

# Pivot to create separate columns for Estimate and MOE
pop_sex_king_2021_long = pop_sex_king_2021_long.pivot(

While the output of pl.get() only has a value column (in the above example, H1_001N in addition to NAME, state and county, ACS output has two columns: estimate and moe after we properly reshape the output to long format.

NB: The moe represents the whole margin of error for a 90% (by default) confidence interval (CI). In other words, estimate + moe will give you the upper limit of a 90% CI and estimate - moe will give you the lower limit.

To calculate the standard error for each estimate when the default 90% margin of error is used, use the following code:

In [ ]:
from scipy import stats
# Calculate standard error
def calculate_se(moe):
     return moe / stats.norm.ppf(0.95)

# Reorder columns
pop_sex_king_2021_long = pop_sex_king_2021_long[['NAME', 'variable', 'estimate', 'moe', 'se', 'state', 'county']]

Below we provide code for pulling counts of individuals by sex and age for King County, Washington from the 2021 ACS using the following information:

  • the dataset: ACS,
  • the dataset-specific variable name: all variables in the description "SEX BY AGE" table B01001,
  • the annual timeframe: year = 2021,
  • the geographic level county in the state of WA and county of King,
  • the temporal scale: using ACS data at county level, let's use 1-year data "acs1",
  • your Census API key

NB: If we wanted info for a county with a population less than 65,000 we would need to get 5-year data for 2017-2021 using acs5.

The census library does not have a built-in function to fetch all variables in a table. Instead, you can use the tables method to get the table metadata and then use the variables URL to get the variable list. We then use the requests library to fetch the variable list from the API.

Using .state_county() for ACS Data¶

Different from .get() method, the .state_county() method is a convenience method specifically for fetching county-level data within a state. It's designed to make it easier to get data for counties without having to specify the full geographic hierarchy. It automatically sets up the correct geographic parameters for you.

Based on the variable names in the step listed above, we then fetch the data for King County, WA, and convert it to a DataFrame.

We can reshape the data to wide format to see the estimate and margin of error for each variable.

Dealing with variable labels¶

Now that we've walked through querying the Census API for the decennial Census and the ACS via the census library, we need to cover some basics to make this data more usable. First and foremost, no one will ever be able to remember what every alphanumeric Census variable NAME is by heart. But, if we use the output of the variables metadata coupled with some data-wrangling, we can get neat string labels in no time! The below example is for the B01001 (SEX BY AGE) table.

Step 1: Get the variables metadata from the API

In [ ]:
# Load variables for the 2021 ACS 1-Year dataset
def get_variables_metadata(year, dataset):
    tables = c.acs1.tables(year=year)
    variables_list = []
    for table in tables:
        if table['name'].startswith('B01001'):  # We're interested in the SEX BY AGE table
            url = table['variables']
            response = requests.get(url)
            variables = response.json()['variables']
            for var_name, var_info in variables.items():
                if var_name not in ['for', 'in']:
                    variables_list.append({
                        'name': var_name,
                        'label': var_info.get('label', ''),
                        'concept': var_info.get('concept', '')
                    })
    return pd.DataFrame(variables_list)

# Split label into sex and age
def split_label(label):
    if isinstance(label, str):
        parts = label.split(':')
        sex = parts[0] if parts[0] in ['Male', 'Female'] else 'Total'
        age = parts[1] if len(parts) > 1 else 'Total'
        return pd.Series([sex, age])
    else:
        return pd.Series(['Total', 'Total'])

Multi-year results¶

One frustrating thing about the census library methods is that they do not allow you to specify more than one year per API query. Below we provide a simple example of how one might pull data for several years without writing a bunch of unnecessary code or doing a lot of copy & pasting that might result in mistakes.

Suppose we want to pull the total population for King County from 2019-2022.

Previously we saw this can be pulled for 2020 from the decennial Census using variable name "P1_001N", and for the 2021 ACS using the variable "B01001_001". NB: While few ACS variable names have changed in recent years, it's worth checking the output of .get() or .state_county() for multiple years just in case. In particular, for years prior to 2010.

We will pull data using a for loop that uses the variable yr to loop over year values of 2019, 2020, 2021, and 2022.

Both the Decennial Census and the ACS results will have the same format with columns named state, county, and the variable name. We will need to modify the variable names into estimate to make it compatible. Finally, we will append a year column to each output before combining them into a single dataset.

In [ ]:
# Variable name strings
dec_var_to_pull = "P1_001N"
acs_var_to_pull = "B01001_001E"

# Years to loop over
years = [2019, 2020, 2021, 2022]

# Empty list to store results
pop_list = []

for yr in years:
    if yr == 2020:
        # Fetch decennial data for 2020
        data = c.pl.state_county(
            (dec_var_to_pull,),
            states.WA.fips,
            '033',  # King County FIPS
            year=yr
        )
        # Convert to DataFrame and add necessary columns
        df = pd.DataFrame(data)
        df = df.rename(columns={"P1_001N": "estimate"})
        df["year"] = yr
    else:
        # Fetch ACS data for other years
        data = c.acs1.state_county(
            (acs_var_to_pull,),
            states.WA.fips,
            '033',  # King County FIPS
            year=yr
        )
        # Convert to DataFrame and add necessary columns
        df = pd.DataFrame(data)
        df = df.rename(columns={"B01001_001E": "estimate"})
        df["year"] = yr
    
    # Append the DataFrame to the list
    pop_list.append(df)

Aggregating estimates across tables¶

Let us return now to our example of sex- and age-specific population. The "B01001" table from the ACS contains population estimates for each sex and age group 0-5, 5-9, 10-14, 15-17, 18-19, 20, 21, 22-24, 25-29, 30-34, 35-39, 40-44, 45-49, 50-54, 55-59, 60-61, 62-64, 65-66, 67-69, 70-74, 75-79, 80-84, and 85+. However, suppose what we want, is actualy 5-year age groups all the way up to 85+. In other words, we want to collapse 20, 21, 22-24 into 20-24, etc. We will need to aggregate both estimates and standard errors properly over age categories.

Recall our rules of expectations and variances below, where $X$ and $Y$ are two random variables and $a$ and $b$ are constants:

$$E[aX + bY] = a\times E[X] + b\times E[Y]$$ $$Var(aX + bY) = a^2 \times Var(X) + b^2 \times Var(Y) + 2ab\times Cov(X,Y).$$ When two variables $X$ and $Y$ are independent, $Cov(X,Y) = 0$, so $$Var(aX + bY) = a^2 \times Var(X) + b^2 \times Var(Y)$$.

So, if we want to aggregate over age groups 20, 21, 22-24, we might consider the real population totals to be denoted $Y_{20}$, $Y_{21}$, and $Y_{22-24}$, so that $Y_{20-24} = Y_{20} + Y_{21} + Y_{22-24}$.

$$E[Y_{20-24}] = E[Y_{20}] + E[Y_{21}] + E[Y_{22-24}].$$

To calculate the variance of $Y_{20-24}$, we need both the variances of each of $Y_{20}$, $Y_{21}$, and $Y_{22-24}$ and the covariances for each pair of those variables. However, the ACS only provides us with their variances.

The best we can do to calculate $Var(Y_{20-24})$ is to assume each covariance is 0. If we assume that the population is sorted into age groups like a multinomial variable, the covariance between the proportion of the population in any two age categories is always negative. This is easy to understand intuitively if we consider the population total fixed. Then, if the proportion in one age category increases, by necessity at least one other age category's must decrease.

So, when we aggregate over age groups 20, 21, and 22-24 and calculate the variance as $$ Var(Y_{20-24}) = Var(Y_{20}) + Var(Y_{21}) + Var(Y_{22-24}),$$ we assume their covariances are equal to 0. While this is not an accurate estimate of the variance of $Y_{20-24}$ we expect it to be an overestimate as we expect the covariances $Cov(Y_{20}, Y_{21}), Cov(Y_{21}, Y_{22-24}), Cov(Y_{20}, Y_{22-24})$ to be negative.

Below we provide code for aggregating ACS 1-year populations by sex and age into 5-year age categories and getting the most accurate standard error we can possible. Recall: the standard error or deviation is the square root of the variance.

def aggregate_age_groups(pop_sex_age_king_2021_labeled):
    # Create a function to map ages to age groups
    def map_age_to_group(age):
        if age == "Total":
            return "Total"
        elif age == "Under 5 years":
            return "0-4"
        elif age in ["15 to 17 years", "18 and 19 years"]:
            return "15-19"
        elif age in ["20 years", "21 years", "22 to 24 years"]:
            return "20-24"
        elif age in ["60 and 61 years", "62 to 64 years"]:
            return "60-64"
        elif age in ["65 and 66 years", "67 to 69 years"]:
            return "65-69"
        elif age == "85 years and over":
            return "85+"
        else:
            return age.replace(" to ", "-").replace(" years", "")

    pop_sex_age5_king_2021 = pop_sex_age_king_2021_labeled.copy()

    # Replace -555555555.0 with NaN for moe
    pop_sex_age5_king_2021['moe'] = pop_sex_age5_king_2021['moe'].replace(-555555555.0, np.nan)

    # Calculate se from moe
    pop_sex_age5_king_2021['se'] = pop_sex_age5_king_2021['moe'] / norm.ppf(0.95)

    # Make new age group
    pop_sex_age5_king_2021['age5'] = pop_sex_age5_king_2021['age'].apply(map_age_to_group)

    # Turn it into a categorical so ages will be considered in correct order
    age_order = ['Total'] + age_groups
    pop_sex_age5_king_2021['age5'] = pd.Categorical(pop_sex_age5_king_2021['age5'], categories=age_order, ordered=True)

    # Separate total and non-total rows
    total_rows = pop_sex_age5_king_2021[pop_sex_age5_king_2021['sex'] == 'Total']
    non_total_rows = pop_sex_age5_king_2021[pop_sex_age5_king_2021['sex'] != 'Total']
    
    # Aggregate over age groups
    pop_sex_age5_king_2021 = non_total_rows.groupby(['GEO_ID', 'state', 'county', 'sex', 'age5']).agg({
        'estimate': 'sum', # E[X +Y] = E[X] + E[Y]
        'se': lambda x: np.sqrt((x**2).sum())  #Var(X + Y) = Var(X) + Var(Y) + Cov(X,Y), SE = sqrt(Var)
    }).reset_index()

    # Round 'se' to 1 decimal place
    pop_sex_age5_king_2021['se'] = pop_sex_age5_king_2021['se'].round(1)
    
    return pop_sex_age5_king_2021

# Apply the aggregation function
pop_sex_age5_king_2021 = aggregate_age_groups(pop_sex_age_king_2021_labeled)
In [ ]:

result = (pop_sex_age_king_2021_labeled[pop_sex_age_king_2021_labeled['age'].isin(['20 years', '21 years', '22 to 24 years'])]
          .assign(se=lambda x: np.round(x['moe'] / norm.ppf(0.95), decimals=1))

Census Geographic Data¶

Census and ACS data are often associated with inherent geographies, which are units at which the data are aggregated. The defined geographies are represented in the U.S. Census Bureau's TIGER/Line database. TIGER stands for Topologically Integrated Geographic Encoding and Referencing and can be simply thought of as the official geographic spatial data of the U.S. Census Bureau.

Spatial data sets are made available as shapefiles and include three general types of data:

(1) Legal entities (e.g. states and counties)

(2) Statistical entities (e.g. Census tracts and block groups)

(3) Geographic features (e.g. roads and water features)

To work with Census geographic data, we suggest the use of the geopandas and uspackages which simplifies the process for Python users of obtaining and using Census geographic data sets.

To start, let's download a shapefile of the states and plot them. We directly download the TIGER/Line shapefile for states from the Census Bureau website. The URL points to the 2021 data, which is equivalent to the default behavior of the tigris package in R.

gpd.read_file() reads the shapefile and creates a GeoDataFrame

Plotting Geographic Data in Python¶

Python offers several options for visualizing geographic data that are useful for geospatial analysis. For ease and intuitiveness, we suggest using geopandas with matplotlib.

For example, to plot Census shapes obtained with geopandas, we can use the above two libraries with the following code. Note that we first reproject the data to WGS84 (latitude/longitude) to ensure correct plotting, and then adjust the tick labels to show degrees.

In [ ]:
# Reproject to WGS84 (latitude/longitude)
seattle_tracts_geo = seattle_tracts.to_crs(epsg=4326)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))
seattle_tracts_geo.plot(ax=ax)
plt.title("Census Tracts in King County, Washington")

# Add latitude and longitude to axes
ax.set_xlabel('Longitude')
ax.set_ylabel('Latitude')

# Adjust tick labels to show degrees
def format_coord(x, y):
    return f'{x:.2f}°W, {y:.2f}°N'

ax.format_coord = format_coord

# Set custom tick locations and labels
xticks = ax.get_xticks()
yticks = ax.get_yticks()
ax.set_xticklabels([f'{abs(x):.1f}°W' for x in xticks])
ax.set_yticklabels([f'{y:.1f}°N' for y in yticks])

plt.show()

In addition to the traditional TIGER/Line shapefiles, the Census Bureau also makes available cartographic boundary shapefiles. These files are derived from the TIGER/Line shapefiles but are generalized in the interior and clipped to the shoreline of the United States, making them a better choice in many cases than the TIGER/Line shapefiles for thematic mapping. This is especially important when dealing with states that have some connection to water/international boundaries.

For Washington counties data set, we can download both the 2022 TIGER/Line and Cartographic Boundary shapefiles and compare them:

In [ ]:
# Download TIGER/Line shapefile for all US counties
url_tiger = "https://www2.census.gov/geo/tiger/TIGER2022/COUNTY/tl_2022_us_county.zip"
us_counties = gpd.read_file(url_tiger)

# Filter for Washington state counties
wa_counties = us_counties[us_counties['STATEFP'] == states.WA.fips]

# Download Cartographic Boundary shapefile for all US counties
url_cb = "https://www2.census.gov/geo/tiger/GENZ2022/shp/cb_2022_us_county_500k.zip"
us_counties_cb = gpd.read_file(url_cb)

# Filter for Washington state counties
wa_counties_cb = us_counties_cb[us_counties_cb['STATEFP'] == states.WA.fips]

# Create two subplots
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 10))

plt.tight_layout()

By default, the plots do not display latitude and longitude on the axes. If you want to add latitude and longitude labels to the axes, please refer to the previous step where we manually added these labels using custom formatting.

For geographic data to appropriately represent locations in mapping and geospatial analysis, they must be referenced to some model of the Earth’s surface correctly. We define this representative model of Earth with a coordinate reference system (CRS), which specifies not only how data coordinates should be mapped to a model of the Earth’s surface but also how measurements should be computed using a given data set.

To access detailed information about the Coordinate Reference System (CRS) in Python, similar to the output you provided, you can use the pyproj library along with geopandas. The pyproj library allows you to access detailed CRS information, including the Well-Known Text (WKT) representation.

For example, let's take another look at our Washington state data:

In [ ]:
# Get the CRS of the data
crs = wa_counties.crs

# Print detailed CRS information
from pyproj import CRS
crs_info = CRS(crs)
print(f"## Coordinate Reference System:\n##   User input: {crs_info.name} \n##   wkt:\n{crs_info.to_wkt()}")

All Census Bureau data sets are stored in the “NAD83” geographic coordinate system, which refers to the North American Datum of 1983. Other relevant information includes the ellipsoid used (GRS 1980, which is a generalized three-dimensional model of the Earth’s shape), the prime meridian of the CRS (Greenwich is used here), and the EPSG (European Petroleum Survey Group) ID of 4269, which is a special code that can be used to represent the CRS in more concise terms.

Thousands of projected CRSs exist in the world. While it can be a challenge to decide on the right projected CRS for your data, the pyproj library can help narrow down the choices.

For example, for the best mapping of our Washington counties data, we could choose:

With a properly projected spatial data set, now we can apply any of the geospatial analyst functions (i.e., spatial overlays, intersections, buffers, etc.) without fear of distortion. From a pure mapping perspective, geographic coordinate systems—in ∘ latitude and longitude—can work, but we suggest to almost always use a properly projected coordinate reference system.

Working with Census Geometries¶

While understanding coordinate reference system transformations is important for spatial data management and geographic visualization, other types of geometric manipulations may be required by the spatial analyst.

A common problem for a national display of the United States is the fragmented nature of US states and territories geographically. The continental United States can be displayed on a map in a relatively straightforward way, and there are a number of projected coordinate reference systems designed for correct display of the continental US. Often, analysts and cartographers then have to make decisions about how to handle Alaska, Hawaii, and Puerto Rico, which cannot be reasonably plotted using default US projections.

For example, let’s take a U.S. state-level shapefile obtained with geopandas at low resolution and use matplotlib to visualize it in the default geographic CRS, NAD 1983:

In [ ]:
# Load the U.S. state-level shapefile
url_states = "https://www2.census.gov/geo/tiger/GENZ2022/shp/cb_2022_us_state_20m.zip"
us_states = gpd.read_file(url_states)

# Plot the states in the default geographic CRS (NAD 1983)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 10))
us_states.plot(ax=ax)
ax.set_title("U.S. States in Default Geographic CRS (NAD 1983)")
plt.show()

The plot does not work well, in part because the Aleutian Islands in far west Alaska cross the 180° of longitude and are plotted on the opposite side of the map.

In response, a projected coordinate reference system appropriate for the United States could be used, such as the continental US Albers Equal Area projection:

In [ ]:
# Define the Albers Equal Area projection for the continental US
albers_equal_area = CRS.from_string("ESRI:102003")

# Transform the CRS
us_states_albers = us_states.to_crs(albers_equal_area)

# Plot the states in the Albers Equal Area projection
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 10))
us_states_albers.plot(ax=ax)
ax.set_title("U.S. States in Albers Equal Area Projection")
plt.show()

While this representation puts all territories in their appropriate locations, it is clearly not appropriate for Alaska, Hawaii, and Puerto Rico which appear distorted.

The tigris package in R offers a solution to this problem with the shift_geometry() function. This function takes an opinionated approach to the shifting and rescaling of Alaska, Hawaii, and Puerto Rico geometries to offer four options for an alternative view of the US. The function works by projecting geometries in Alaska, Hawaii, and Puerto Rico to appropriate coordinate reference systems for those areas, then re-sizing the geometries (if requested) and moving them to an alternative layout in relationship to the rest of the US using the Albers Equal Area CRS.

In Python, we can achieve a similar result using custom transformations and adjustments. Here is an example of how you might do this:

In [ ]:
from shapely.affinity import translate, scale
# Function to shift and scale geometries
def shift_and_scale_geometries(gdf, state_fips, xoff, yoff, scale_factor=1.0):
    state_gdf = gdf[gdf['STATEFP'] == state_fips]
    state_gdf = state_gdf.copy()
    state_gdf['geometry'] = state_gdf['geometry'].apply(lambda geom: translate(scale(geom, xfact=scale_factor, yfact=scale_factor, origin='center'), xoff=xoff, yoff=yoff))
    return state_gdf
# Shift and scale Alaska, Hawaii, and Puerto Rico
alaska = shift_and_scale_geometries(us_states_albers, '02', xoff=-3000000, yoff=-2500000, scale_factor=0.35)
hawaii = shift_and_scale_geometries(us_states_albers, '15', xoff=5200000, yoff=-1400000, scale_factor=1.0)
puerto_rico = shift_and_scale_geometries(us_states_albers, '72', xoff=4500000, yoff=500000, scale_factor=1.0)

# Combine the shifted geometries with the rest of the states
contiguous_us = us_states_albers[~us_states_albers['STATEFP'].isin(['02', '15', '72'])]
us_states_shifted = pd.concat([contiguous_us, alaska, hawaii, puerto_rico])

# Plot the shifted geometries
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 10))
us_states_shifted.plot(ax=ax, color='lightgrey', edgecolor='black')

# Set minimal theme
ax.set_title("U.S. States with Shifted Alaska, Hawaii, and Puerto Rico")
ax.set_axis_off()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.colors as colors

# Ensure 'estimate' is numeric and replace -666666666.0 with NaN
dc_income['estimate'] = pd.to_numeric(dc_income['B19013_001E'], errors='coerce')
dc_income['estimate'] = dc_income['estimate'].replace(-666666666.0, np.nan)

# Create a custom colormap similar to the R default
colors_list = ['#0000FF', '#4B0082', '#8B008B', '#FF1493', '#FF69B4', '#FFB6C1', '#FFFF00']
n_bins = len(colors_list)
cmap = colors.ListedColormap(colors_list)
bounds = np.linspace(dc_income['estimate'].min(), dc_income['estimate'].max(), n_bins + 1)
norm = colors.BoundaryNorm(bounds, cmap.N)

# Create the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10))

# Plot the data
dc_income.plot(column='estimate', ax=ax, cmap=cmap, norm=norm,
               edgecolor='black', linewidth=0.5,
               missing_kwds={'color': 'white', 'edgecolor': 'black'},
               legend_kwds={'label': 'Median Household Income ($)',
                            'orientation': 'horizontal'})
# Remove axes
ax.axis('off')

# Add a title
ax.set_title('Median Household Income ($)', fontsize=16, loc='center', pad=20)

# Add colorbar
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
sm.set_array([])

Map-Making with Matplotlib and Geopandas¶

Matplotliband Geopandas can be used for plotting of GeoDataFrames in Python.

Let's consider the 2019 ACS 1-year estimates for median age by state:

In [ ]:
# Fetch ACS data for median age by state for all states
us_median_age_data = []
for state in states.STATES:
    data = c.acs1.state(
        fields=["B01002_001E"],
        state_fips=state.fips,
        year=2019
    )
    us_median_age_data.extend(data)

# Convert to DataFrame
us_median_age_df = pd.DataFrame(us_median_age_data)

Areal interpolation¶

Areal interpolation is the process of estimating values from a source set of polygons to an overlapping but non-congruent set of target polygons. This technique is helpful when a project requires spatial analysis at a scale not included in the Census enumerations.

In Python, we can perform areal interpolation using libraries such as geopandas and rasterstats.

Let's consider a problem where HOLC Neighborhood designations are used to express socioeconomic and demographic data.

First, we'll read in the HOLC spatial data and plot it according to neighborhood designation. Shreveport, Louisiana HOLC designations are found here.

To calculate the total population within HOLC neighborhood grades, we need to perform areal interpolation, adjusting the Census tract data to match the spatial dimensions of the HOLC neighborhoods.

We start by adding an "ID" column to both spatial datasets, which is necessary for the area_interpolate() function to work correctly. It's also crucial to ensure that the Coordinate Reference System (CRS) for each spatial dataset is projected in the same reference system. We accomplish this using the to_crs() method in geopandas.

We use the tobler library, specifically the area_interpolate() function, which is analogous to the aw_interpolate() function in R's areal package. This function performs area-weighted interpolation, estimating population values for the HOLC neighborhoods based on the overlapping Census tracts.

The process involves the following steps:

  1. Adding unique ID columns to both the HOLC and Census tract datasets.
  2. Transforming both datasets to the same CRS (EPSG:5070 in this case).
  3. Performing the areal interpolation using area_interpolate().
  4. Rounding the interpolated population values to whole numbers. T his approach allows us to estimate the population within each HOLC neighborhood grade, providing a way to analyze demographic patterns in relation to historical redlining practices.
In [ ]:
from tobler.area_weighted import area_interpolate

# Add ID columns
ShreveportHOLC['ID'] = range(1, len(ShreveportHOLC) + 1)
shreveport_pop['ID2'] = range(1, len(shreveport_pop) + 1)

# Ensure CRS is the same for both datasets
ShreveportHOLC = ShreveportHOLC.to_crs(epsg=4326).to_crs(epsg=5070)
shreveport_pop = shreveport_pop.to_crs(epsg=5070)

# Perform areal interpolation
interpolated_output = area_interpolate(
    source_df=shreveport_pop,
    target_df=ShreveportHOLC,
    extensive_variables=['Total_Pop'],
    intensive_variables=None,
    allocate_total=True
)
# Round the interpolated values
interpolated_output['Total_Pop'] = np.round(interpolated_output['Total_Pop']).astype(int)

# Print column names
print("Available columns:", interpolated_output.columns)

# Select columns to display
display_columns = ['Total_Pop']
if 'ID' in interpolated_output.columns:
    display_columns.insert(0, 'ID')
if 'grade' in interpolated_output.columns:
    display_columns.insert(1, 'grade')
